[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can I start off by asking you all to comment on how satisfied you are overall with the progress since 2012 by the Crown Estate Commissioners in making themselves more responsive to local communities?
[normal] 
[normal]We have been told that there is a positive direction of travel, is there any real, meaningful evidence of that?
[normal]Cllr Angus Campbell:[bold] Speaking for ourselves, I would say that we haven’t seen much evidence of that at all.
[normal] 
[normal]In fact, many of the same issues that we brought up in evidence the first time are st
[normal]ill there—in regards to leases and 
[normal]information to the community
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]alking about moving forward with marine renewables is very important to the 
[normal]Islands
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We 
[normal]are on the receiving end of decisions as to where things go and where they might happen.
[normal] 
[normal]The one issue that seems to have been promoted as a change is the local area agreements.
[normal] 
[normal]I actually visited the group that 
[normal]got 
[normal]the first one, Comann na Mara 
[normal]down in 
[normal]Lochmaddy, and I have to say it is much more in the nature of a commercial loan than what I would say is a 
[normal]local management agreement
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]I would expect a lot more for the community in any of these 
[normal]local management agreements than
[normal] what I saw there last week.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can I just clarify one point?
[normal] 
[normal]You are here representing the three 
[normal]Island
[normal] authorities, as I understand it, in regard to the issues that you have just raised are you speaking on behalf of the seven? There was a document that came forward from all of the Highlands and Islands authorities together, seven in total
[normal]; 
[normal]is what you are saying an accurate representation of their views as a whole or jus
[normal]t
[normal] the Island authorities?
[normal]Cllr Angus Campbell:[bold] I would hope it is
[normal], but I hesitate to say that for sure because the seven authorities have not got together on that issue in the recent past, whereas the three 
[normal]Island
[normal] authorities have taken a position on the Crown Estate as regards our islands, our future.
[normal] 
[normal]That document states very clearly where we are, which is very much in line with the document the seven produced in the last period.
[normal] 
[normal]There is continuity 
[normal]and
[normal] agreement there.
[normal] 
[normal]I would hope I speak for the seven local authorities
[normal] still
[normal], but it is not something I discussed with them before coming to this meeting.
[normal]Peter Peacock[bold]: I think at a fundamental level we argued in our evidence to you about the Crown Estate that we thought that communities who own their land should have, by right, ownership of the foreshore adjacent to their land; it is part of the resource that they require to give themselves a long term sustainable future.
[normal] 
[normal]We also argued that communities should have control of an inner zone of seabed for largely similar purposes.
[normal] 
[normal]At a fundamental level the Crown Estate maintain the position that existed before your Committee reported, 
[normal]so
[normal] in that kind of structural sense
[normal],
[normal] I don’t think it could be said that there has been significant movement.
[normal] 
[normal]Having said that, 
[normal]I should 
[normal]in fairness
[normal] say that
[normal] we have had discussions with the Crown Estate
[normal], and the 
[normal]new chief executive—not new now, but new at the time—was clearly focused on trying to move things along
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We 
[normal]understand they are in the process of devising a scheme to transfer foreshore to communities who already own the land adjacent to that foreshore.
[normal] 
[normal]We have still to engage with them on that—that is partly our fault
[normal];
[normal] we have had other priorities this year and 
[normal]have 
[normal]not been focused on that—but there is some indication of movement there.
[normal] 
[normal]Angus Campbell 
[normal]talked
[normal] about the 
[normal]local management agreements. One 
[normal]of our members has recently entered one of those agreements with the Crown Estate
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]e are planning to unpack that with them and see what is actually in there for local communities.
[normal] 
[normal]So 
[normal]I detect some movement, but it
[normal] i
[normal]s not at the more fundamental level that we argued for in principle with your Committee.
[normal]Angus Robertson[bold]: I am deferring to Peter on Crown Estate matters.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Reid:[bold] [bold]I think it
[normal] was Angus who referred to the fact that you would expect a lot more from the 
[normal]local management agreements. W
[normal]hat would 
[normal]you 
